      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        The Form 6 Agency Authority: What Brisbane Sellers Sign When Engaging an Agent
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The Form 6 is the legal document that gives your agent authority to act on your behalf. Most sellers sign it under time pressure at an appraisal meeting. Here is what to read before you do.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The Form 6 is not a formality. It is a legally binding contract between you and your real estate agent, and it governs the entire relationship from the moment you sign until after the property is sold. Most sellers do not read it carefully before signing. This is partly because appraisal meetings move quickly, agents are understandably focused on building rapport, and the paperwork feels like an administrative hurdle rather than a substantive decision. But the Form 6 contains several clauses that directly affect what you pay, who has the right to sell your property, and what obligations continue after the authority period ends.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a Form 6 is and why it is required</h2>
      <p>The Form 6 is the property agent appointment form prescribed under the Property Occupations Act 2014 (Queensland). The Act requires that a real estate agent hold a written authority from a seller before they can market or sell that seller's property. Without a signed Form 6, no advertising can lawfully run and no commission can be charged. The form can be signed electronically and is typically presented at or shortly after the appraisal meeting.</p>

      <p>The form is standardised in its structure but not in its commercial terms. The authority period, commission rate, marketing spend cap, and any special conditions are all negotiable and will reflect what has been agreed between you and the agent. Understanding each field before you sign is the minimum standard of self-protection a seller should apply.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The authority period: exclusive versus open agency</h2>
      <p>The authority period is the length of time the agent is appointed to sell your property. There are two main types of authority: exclusive and open.</p>

      <p>An exclusive agency authority means that only the appointed agent has the right to sell during the authority period. If the property sells through any party during that period, including through your own efforts as the owner, the agent is entitled to their commission. Exclusive agency is the standard arrangement in Queensland and is what most full-service agents will require. In return for exclusivity, you should expect a committed marketing program, regular reporting, and accountability from the agent.</p>

      <p>An open agency authority allows you to appoint multiple agents simultaneously. Commission is payable only to the agent who introduces the buyer who actually completes the purchase. Open agencies are less common in residential property in Brisbane because agents are reluctant to invest in marketing a property where they may not be the ones to earn the commission. If an agent agrees to an open authority, clarify upfront what marketing they will commit to under those terms.</p>

      <p>Authority periods in Queensland are typically 60 to 90 days for exclusive listings, though longer periods are sometimes used in slower markets or for premium properties that may take longer to find the right buyer. You can negotiate the length. A shorter initial period with the option to extend is reasonable to request if you are uncertain about the agent or the market conditions. A well-prepared property with appropriate pricing should not need six months of authority.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The marketing expense cap: what the agent can spend without your approval</h2>
      <p>The Form 6 includes a marketing expense cap: the maximum amount the agent is authorised to spend on your behalf without seeking further approval from you. Marketing costs typically include portal listing fees (realestate.com.au and Domain), professional photography, floor plans, print advertising, and any signage. The cap should reflect the agreed marketing budget discussed with the agent.</p>

      <p>Read the cap carefully. If the figure is higher than the marketing budget you discussed, query it before signing. Some agents set a high cap as a matter of course; others specifically match it to the agreed program. You should never be presented with a marketing invoice that exceeds the cap in the Form 6 without having been asked first. If the cap is lower than the full marketing commitment, confirm in writing what the remaining costs will be and when they will be invoiced.</p>

      <p>Marketing costs in Brisbane's inner east for a well-run campaign typically run from $3,000 to $6,000 depending on the property and the extent of the program. Premium listings on the major portals are the largest single cost. Your agent should be able to itemise the expected spend so you know exactly what is covered within the cap.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Commission rate and structure</h2>
      <p>The Form 6 records the commission rate, the basis on which it is calculated (percentage of sale price, fixed fee, or a tiered structure), and at what point it becomes payable. Commission in Queensland is not regulated, meaning the rate is a commercial agreement between the agent and the seller.</p>

      <p>Percentage commission in Queensland typically ranges from 2% to 3% of the sale price, though this varies by market, agent, and property value. Tiered commission structures, where the rate increases above a specified price threshold, are designed to incentivise the agent to push for a higher price. They are worth understanding: if your property is priced at $1,200,000 with a tiered structure that increases commission above $1,200,000, the agent has a clear incentive to secure a price above that threshold, which generally aligns with your interest as the seller.</p>

      <p>Commission is typically payable on settlement, not on the signing of the contract. Confirm this in the Form 6. Also confirm what happens to commission if the sale does not complete, such as if the buyer defaults after the contract becomes unconditional. The answer will depend on the specific circumstances and whether the agent is entitled to commission regardless of whether you recover damages from the defaulting buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Rebate disclosure: what agents must tell you</h2>
      <p>Under the Property Occupations Act, agents are required to disclose any rebates, commissions, or other benefits they receive from third parties in connection with your sale. This commonly applies to referral arrangements with property portals, photographers, or other service providers where the agent receives a volume discount or a referral payment.</p>

      <p>The Form 6 includes a rebate disclosure section. Read it. If an agent receives a rebate from realestate.com.au because they purchase a high volume of listings, they are legally required to disclose that in the Form 6 even if the rebate does not directly affect your marketing fee. This transparency is required by law. If the rebate section is blank when you would expect something to be there, ask the agent to confirm in writing that no rebates apply.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Conjunctional agency: when another agent is involved</h2>
      <p>Some Form 6 authorities include a conjunctional agency clause, which allows your appointed agent to share the listing with another agent and split commission if that second agent introduces the buyer. Conjunctional arrangements are common in some markets and can broaden the buyer pool, but they also mean your property is being marketed through a party you have not directly appointed.</p>

      <p>If your Form 6 includes a conjunctional clause, understand what conditions apply: whether your consent is required for each conjunctional arrangement, how the commission is split, and whether the second agent has access to your personal information. An agent who operates conjunctionally should be transparent about when and why they would bring in another party.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The continuing agency clause: commissions after the authority ends</h2>
      <p>The continuing agency clause is one of the most consequential clauses in the Form 6 and the one sellers are most likely to overlook. It provides that even after the authority period expires, the agent retains the right to commission if the property is sold to a buyer who was introduced by the agent during the authority period.</p>

      <p>In practical terms, this means that if your authority with Agent A expires, you appoint Agent B, and Agent B's eventual buyer turns out to be someone Agent A showed through an open home six months earlier, Agent A may still be entitled to commission. Both agents would then have a claim, which creates a dispute you would rather not be in the middle of.</p>

      <p>The clause typically specifies a tail period, usually 6 to 12 months after the authority expires, during which the continuing claim applies. Check the duration in your Form 6. When moving between agents, your solicitor or the new agent should confirm whether any buyers they are working with were previously introduced by the prior agent, to avoid a dispute emerging after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Terminating the authority early</h2>
      <p>The Property Occupations Act provides a 1-business-day cooling-off period for residential agency authorities. If you sign a Form 6 and change your mind within 1 business day, you can terminate without incurring a financial penalty, provided you give written notice to the agent.</p>

      <p>After the cooling-off period, early termination is possible but typically exposes you to the agent's reasonable costs incurred to that point, which can include photography, portal listings, and any advertising already placed. The Form 6 should specify what costs are recoverable on early termination. If you are considering appointing an agent but are not fully committed, ask about the cooling-off provisions and costs before signing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Red flags in non-standard Form 6 additions</h2>
      <p>Most Form 6 authorities in Queensland use the standard REIQ template. Additions or amendments that go beyond the standard terms warrant careful reading. Common additions that deserve scrutiny include clauses that remove the cooling-off period (this is sometimes included but should be knowingly agreed to, not buried in fine print), clauses that expand the continuing agency tail period beyond 12 months, marketing caps that are substantially higher than the agreed marketing program, and clauses that require the seller to pay marketing costs upfront regardless of whether the property sells.</p>

      <p>Non-standard additions are not automatically unreasonable, but they should be additions you have actively agreed to, not provisions you discover after signing. If anything in the Form 6 is unclear, ask the agent to explain it before you sign, or take the document to a solicitor for review. The right agent will not be offended by a seller who reads carefully.</p>

